<DOC><DOCNO> AP880315-0077 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 0908EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Grippo     03-15 0216</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Obit-Grippo,0224</SECOND><HEAD>`Bowery Boys' Producer Dead at 81</HEAD><DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Jan Grippo, who in the 1940s and 1950sproduced nearly two dozen ``Bowery Boys'' movies, has died at theage of 81.   The New York native produced at least 23 films featuring theband of impish juvenile delinquents, whose ranks included wise guyLeo Gorcey and his naive patsy, Huntz Hall.   Grippo died Saturday at a Los Angeles hospital.   Although the ``Bowery Boys'' started off as troublemakers in thefilms ``Dead End'' and ``Angels With Dirty Faces,'' it was Grippo,as their agent, who cleaned them up for their popular series.   ``Jan wanted them to get into trouble, but to be good kids atheart,'' said his wife, Paula Grippo.   Born in Beacon, N.Y., Grippo began his career as a cartoonistfor the New York Herald-Tribune Syndicate. He came to Hollywood in1937 to become an agent.   During World War II, Grippo was active with the HollywoodCanteen, a gathering place for those in the military.   A magician by hobby, he was a member of both the Society ofAmerican Magicians and the Academy of Magical Arts and oftenpracticed at the Magic Castle in Hollywood.   Grippo is survived by his wife, three brothers, James, Michaeland Henry, and a sister, Bertha DeLucca.</TEXT></DOC>